Matthis did not wake hungry, like usual. His stomach did not hurt. But his bones did. 

He washed his face in the basin. He checked the box under the table that held the basin. He found little crumbs of sage and juniper. He had hoped to light some this morning to cut the smell of rot.

He knelt beside his cot and fished under it with his hands. He pulled out a small pouch of coins and placed them in his satchel. 

Outside, the wizard stood in the same spot as the night before. But its sockets pointed at Matthis. He froze. The black skull slowly turned its head away. It watched the cages. 

Matthis shivered. 

He spread the ash where he had burned the wizard's old flesh and clothing. It was cold. Then he stopped along the cages. The skeletons stirred, but he stayed out of their attack range. The locking pins had worn down from rust. He took a step toward a skeleton. It sprang forward and clawed at him. He didn't like the way the pins rattled. 

He adjusted his satchel and made his way to the square. The sky was watery gray this morning. He stopped. He looked back. 

The black skeleton made no move to follow him. 

"Oi," he called. 

The black skull turned. It looked at him. Then it slowly turned back. It stared at the gibbets. 

Matthis walked backward. He stopped. He turned and walked a few feet and looked back. 

The wizard did not move.

--

The smithy smelled of coal fire, heat, and oiled metal. The smith pumped a bellows larger than him. A leather apron blanketed his round belly. His wide beard curled down to his collarbone. His arms looked as hard as the metal he forged. 

"Locking pins?" he asked when Matthis approached. He drew red metal out of the stone forged and hammered it.

"Goodman Foster --"

"Oh, quit that. Just call me Foss."

Matthis blinked. "How did you know?"

"Iron rusts." He set the metal in the fire and placed the tongs on the anvil. "So how many are weak? All seven?"

Matthis stared. Not two days ago, there were eight gibbets. 

Foss grunted. "I saw the eighth one after the mine rumble. Turned to thread? Wizard's magic. Odd that."

Matthis nodded. "I thought nails would do the trick this time. To replace the pins."

Foss grunted. "They would." He patted his anvil with his gloved hand. "Right tool, right job, though."

Matthis didn't have a response to that. So he pulled his money pouch from his satchel. But Foss waved it away. 

"Come back tomorrow. We'll talk weights and scales after you see your new pins."

Foss gathered the tongs and returned to the forge. He pumped the bellows. Matthis closed his mouth and dropped the money pouch in his satchel. 

"The bars on those gibbets look a bit rusted, too. Imagine trying to treat them with a skeleton scratching at you."

"You'll get them back one day," Matthis promised. "The skeletons will not hang there forever." He wasn't sure he had convinced himself.

"Keep a sharp eye on them. If the rust isn't too deep, something might be saved."

The forge roared with every pump of the bellows. The smith bounced his hammer on the anvil. The metal sang with the morning birds.

Foss said, "Good day," as Matthis walked away. 

--

Matthis knocked on the apothecary door. For the third time. He tapped his foot. The sky had turned iron gray.

"Hold on, hold on," said a muffled voice inside. "Dawn does not crack like a whip for all of us, you know."

A white head poked out of the door. A pair of bloodshot eyes turned up to Matthis.

"Sorry to wake you, Master Phineas."

"Well." The man blinked at him like an owl. "At least you're polite. Vinegar?" He turned inside and didn't bother to open the door any wider. 

Matthis hesitated and walked into a wall of scents that made his eyes burn. One wall was made entirely of shelves, floor to ceiling. Bundles of herbs wrapped in cloth, beeswax candles, bottles of every size. He felt a bit dizzy. 

"And sage and juniper."

"You'll want wormwood as well. It keeps flies away. You'll find that useful, in your work." 

Phineas ducked behind the counter. It was laden with three differently sized mortars and pestles. He emerged with a stool, which he used to climb to a shelf Matthis could have reached. But Matthis knew better than to touch anything.

Matthis noticed a set of bottles that he recognized as laudanum. He had needed some two winters ago. 

Phineas returned to the counter with three sets of herbs tied with string, a bottle, and a bundle of cloth.

"You'll want lye soap as well. It's tough on the skin, so be careful with it." Phineas blinked with his eyebrows. 

Matthis did need soap, so he didn't argue. He pulled out his coins and counted a few into Phineas' hand. 

The little man nodded. "That's the price we negotiated last time. Good enough. Come back after dawn next time."

Matthis had just enough time to place his items in his satchel before the door closed behind him. He smiled to himself and shook his head. Always the same, Master Phineas. 

Thunder rolled overhead. The air stilled. Matthis pulled his coat tighter around him.

"Oh good I found you."

Rafe waved at Matthis around a draft horse hauling timber. The buildings lining the dirt street had once been white. They were now smudged with soot. Rafe picked his way around the draft horse. The driver had wrapped himself in a thick hooded cloak. He raised a gloved hand in Rafe's direction. 

"We've been summoned to the Miner's Guild house," said Rafe.

Matthis felt a drop on his hand and wished he had thought to wear his heavier jacket. He squinted at the sky. 

"What does Corven want?"

"It's not just him, Matthis," said Rafe. His lips were thin and white. The usual playful spark in his eyes was gone. "The Vicar and Mercy are there as well. They want us both."

Matthis clenched the strap of his satchel in both fists. He followed Rafe, whose shoulders had stiffened. They weaves between buildings. The air smelled of soot and rain. 

--

The coal yard smelled of iron and wet stone. Workers swung hammers on stone with loud pings and cracking sounds. Their movements were smooth and deft. A man with his leg missing to the knee sat in the mud and bashed rocks with a hammer. He placed large black pieces into one basket and smaller coal nuts into another. Over the splash of mud and rain, Matthis heard nearby yard workers complain. 

"Hate the rain. Always have. Dead depressing this is."

"I've swapped dust in me lungs for water in me boots."

A child of perhaps ten or twelve made the others look inept. He cracked stone and sorted coal in almost the same motion. Black water trickled down a narrow trench along one side of the yard.

Lightning flashed. Everyone froze. Matthis counted to twelve. Work resumed more slowly after the low rumble. Rafe and Matthis ducked into the guild house. 

The long chamber was lined with magic lanterns. It smelled of sweat and wood smoke. A fire flickered at the far end. Corven and the Vicar occupied stools on either side of the wide hearth. Mercy stood in the Vicar's shadow, her hands folded before her. The floor rumbles under Rafe and Matthis' feet. 

"Good you're here," said Corven. "We can get started."

The guild master's coat might have looked fancy once. Now the coal dust was weaved into the fibers. The callouses in his leathery hands weren't as deep as some. But they were stained just as black. Corven sat with his back straighter than any miner's. But the man knew the mine better than any of them. Corven was one of the few in Coalridge who could read. But Matthis suspected his hair didn't naturally grow coal black.

"The Vicar and I," said Corven, "have decided that the town should own the Death Guild."

Mercy's feet shifted. Hands folded in his lap, the Vicar looked up at Matthis and back to the fire. Rafe's fists clenched.

"You and I both know it was just a name," said Matthis. "The Death Guild doesn't exist."

"Every town," said the Vicar, "must care for its dead. We've supported Rafe. You will both manage the Death Guild together."

"I don't know why we didn't do this to begin with," said Corven. "I stop paying for a public service that's already provided by the town anyway. The Death Guild gets legitimacy from the town, not the Miner's Guild." Corven clapped his hands. "Everyone wins."

Matthis glimpsed a smile on Mercy's lips. Rafe's knuckles turned white. Corven's eyes danced with the firelight. The Vicar's shoulders sagged a little. 

"What will this change?" said Matthis. 

Corven's smile faltered a little. The Vicar cleared his throat. 

"Very little." The Vicar sighed. "You will remain guild master. You and Rafe will work together." He rubbed his hands and held them over the fire. "Just keep peace with the dead."

Matthis rubbed his neck and shrugged. "Do I sign something?"

Mercy stepped forward and handed a roll of vellum parchment to the Vicar. He unrolled it and passed it to Corven, who read it and nodded.

"Your handwriting is very neat, Vicar."

Corven passed the document to Matthis. Matthis held it up. He couldn't tell if it was upside down or not. 

"What happens if I sign?" said Matthis. "Will I answer to the Vicar?"

"You'll answer to the people of the town," said Mercy. 

"The pay will be the same," said Corven with a shrug.

"You will be master of the Death Guild," said the Vicar, "and your responsibilities will not change."

Matthis took a quill from Corven and dipped it in an ink bottle on the mantle piece. He propped the parchment on his knee and scrawled his name where Corven pointed. The Vicar powdered the ink before it could bleed and thanked everyone. Mercy glided out the door behind him and into sheets of rain. 

"Could I have a word, Matthis?" Corven asked. 

Rafe squeezed Matthis' shoulder. "Meet me at the Oak and Ember?"

Corven leaned forward on his stool and held his hands toward the fire. Matthis stared at the flames. Rafe closed the door.

"Tell me," he said, his fingers steepled under his chin, "about that black skeleton."

Matthis didn't like the way Corven said it. He narrowed his eyes. Corven raised his eyebrows. 

"You want to know if they can swing a pickaxe," Matthis whispered. 

Corven smiled. "Look, Matthis. If it can swing a hammer or an axe, I'll pay you half wages for every skeleton that works for me."

Matthis stared at the man. He ground his teeth. 

"Every one of those men," he said, "died working in your mine."

Corven couldn't hold Matthis' gaze. He folded his arms and looked at the fire instead.

"And now you want them working for you after death?"

Corven turned his head away and brushed his mustache. Black dust fell out of it. "It couldn't hurt to ask what they want," he grumbled. "Forget I asked. You can go."

Matthis paced his way out of the guild house. He barely noticed the rain. Thunder crashed, and he felt it in his chest. He tilted his head toward the black sky. Marthis sloshed his way to the Oak and Ember.

Ask them what they want. 
 